<br>
Afterall, when was the last time you had a gas outage, vs an electrical outage?  <br>
<br>
The problem with PV at residences is twofold: <br>
<br>
1) It's EXPENSIVE.  Maybe it'll get cheaper someday, maybe not.<br>
<br>
2) Distributed systems have inherent inefficiencys of scale.  The reverse of economies of scale, and these are complicated by what I crudely term &quot;The Idiot Factor.&quot;  IE, there is a percentage of the population that can readily handle our current system, but if faced with running, managing, and maintaining their own power source can be relied upon to kill themselves on it.  Sad, but true.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Now, PASSIVE solar is a much more efficient way of doing Solar power, but I can say from experience that it is not all it is cracked up to be.  In other words, passive solar works great, but it can be uncomfortable and/or a pain in the butt.<br>
